{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12858"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12858"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.35,0.07,0.07,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114340"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5301"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96340"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"124"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47520"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114340"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of colour changes in her fingers and toes which occur when exposed to cold temperatures or during moments of stress. She has had these symptoms for about three years and describes her fingers turning white, then blue and finally red before returning to their normal colour. The episodes are accompanied by tingling sensations, numbness, and mild pain in the affected areas. Her fingers feel unusually tight and she has noticed changes in her skin texture with her skin becoming shiny and taut. She finds it difficult to flex and extend her fingers fully.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is non-pitting oedema on her fingers with shiny, taut skin and evidence of nicotine staining, accompanied by erythema and dilatation of capillary loops in her nail-fold bed with the disappearance of skin creases. On inspection of her face, there is tightness and thinning of the skin, particularly around her mouth, resulting in a limited range of motion while speaking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome treatment will be instituted whilst arrangements are made for some diagnostic investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the preferred initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluoxetine","Amlodipine","Iloprost","Sildenafil","Avoid cold exposure and stop smoking"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has presented with Raynaud phenomenon which is caused by vasospasm of the digits, usually in response to cold exposure or stress. Raynaud phenomenon can be a primary condition or can occur secondary to a connective tissue disease (eg systemic sclerosis) or other disease (eg atherosclerosis, malignancy). An underlying connective tissue disease should be suspected in a patient with other common clinical features of a connective tissue disease (eg arthralgia, fatigue) and abnormal nail fold capillaries on inspection under magnification (eg dilatation, capillary dropout, haemorrhage). These patients would also have an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and a positive antinuclear antibody (ANA). Secondary Raynaud phenomenon may cause digital ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to guidelines, the initial management options for patients presenting with Raynaud phenomenon is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eavoid cold exposure and stop smoking\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the first line option while the patient is being investigated to exclude any secondary cause which may then need to be treated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a dihydropyridine-type calcium antagonist is the first-line drug for the treatment of Raynauds phenomenon in patients with an underlying connective tissue disorder such as systemic sclerosis and has proven to reduce the frequency and severity of ischaemic attacks with a considerably safer profile of side effects. But it is not the first-line option while the patient is being investigated for the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine, \u003C/strong\u003Ean SSRI is an unconventional choice for the treatment of Raynaud phenomenon but a \u003Ca href=\u0022Coleiro%20B,%20Marshall%20SE,%20Denton%20CP,%20Howell%20K,%20Blann%20A,%20Welsh%20KI,%20Black%20CM.%20Treatment%20of%20Raynaud\u0027s%20phenomenon%20with%20the%20selective%20serotonin%20reuptake%20inhibitor%20fluoxetine.%20Rheumatology%20(Oxford).%202001%20Sep;40(9)%3A1038-43.%20doi%3A%2010.1093/rheumatology/40.9.1038.%20PMID:%2011561116.\u0022\u003Estudy\u003C/a\u003E has demonstrated its role in the treatment of Raynaud phenomenon especially in systemic sclerosis. The data for the use of fluoxetine in this role is limited and along with its side effects profile, it is usually avoided and only used in selected patients who cannot tolerate or respond to vasodilators.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIloprost\u003C/strong\u003E, a prostanoid is known to reduce the frequency and severity of Raynaud phenomenon in systemic sclerosis, especially in intravenous form. But it is not the first line of treatment and is usually employed after initial therapy with nifedipine or sildenafil has failed after the confirmation of an underlying connective tissue disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESildenafil\u003C/strong\u003E, a phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE-5) inhibitor can be used in this patient, but it is usually used in the severe form of Raynaud phenomenon after confirmation of an underlying connective tissue disorder such as systemic sclerosis or when there is an unsatisfactory response to initial nifedipine therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Advising the patient to avoid cold exposure and stop smoking is the initial management of choice for Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon while the patient is being investigated for underlying disease.","Raynaud phenomenon can be primary or secondary, often associated with connective tissue diseases like systemic sclerosis.","Nifedipine is the first-line pharmacological treatment for Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon in patients with an underlying connective tissue disorder."],"references":["Kowal-Bielecka O, Fransen J, Avouac J, Becker M, Kulak A, Allanore Y, Distler O, Clements P, Cutolo M, Czirjak L, Damjanov N, Del Galdo F, Denton CP, Distler JHW, Foeldvari I, Figelstone K, Frerix M, Furst DE, Guiducci S, Hunzelmann N, Khanna D, Matucci-Cerinic M, Herrick AL, van den Hoogen F, van Laar JM, Riemekasten G, Silver R, Smith V, Sulli A, Tarner I, Tyndall A, Welling J, Wigley F, Valentini G, Walker UA, Zulian F, M\u00fcller-Ladner U; EUSTAR Coauthors. Update of EULAR recommendations for the treatment of systemic sclerosis. Ann Rheum Dis. 2017 Aug;76(8):1327-1339. doi: 10.1136/annrheumdis-2016-209909. Epub 2016 Nov 9. PMID: 27941129.","O\u0027connor CM. Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon. J Vasc Nurs. 2001 Sep;19(3):87-92; quiz 93-4. doi: 10.1067/mvn.2001.117786. PMID: 11533581.","Nawaz I, Nawaz Y, Nawaz E, Manan MR, Mahmood A. Raynaud\u0027s Phenomenon: Reviewing the Pathophysiology and Management Strategies. Cureus. 2022 Jan 28;14(1):e21681. doi: 10.7759/cureus.21681. PMID: 35242466; PMCID: PMC8884459."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T15:59:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T16:00:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5301"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114340"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"u